===Phonosemantic interpretation===

[[w:Old_Chinese|Old Chinese]] [[w:Old_Chinese_phonology#Initials|Initial]] {{IPAchar|/*t-/}} lends semantic value '''Straight'''.
{{liushu|p}} of a leg/foot come to a stop, making the body stand straight upright. Specifically, the reference is to a servant standing straight (by) in awaiting orders (compare [[寺]]).
Source: [http://www.kanjinetworks.com/eng/kanji-dictionary/online-kanji-etymology-dictionary.cfm?kanji_id=TAG51 Howell & Morimoto]

===Etymology===
{{liushu|p}} – a footprint. Compare {{term|手||hand|sc=Hani}}. Note that in oracle script, composed of 3 toes and a sole.

Compare to [[夊]], [[夂]], which have similar shape in oracle script, but pointing down (toe pointing right), and [[𡕒]] (as in right side of [[舛]], roughly [[ヰ]], toe pointing left), hence different evolution.

